TRANSALTA ENERGY MARKETING (U.S.) INC. RATE SCHEDULE NO. 2 SALE, ASSIGNMENT, OR TRANSFER OF TRANSMISSION RIGHTS ON NON-JURISDICTIONAL TRANSMITTING UTILITY SYSTEMS 1. General Purpose: The purpose of this rate schedule is to provide for the sale, assignment, or transfer of transmission rights by TransAlta Energy Marketing (U.S.) Inc. ("Seller") on non-jurisdictional transmitting utility systems in which the transmission provider does not play the intermediary role in secondary market transmission transactions as contemplated under the reforms that the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission ("Commission") adopted in Order No. 890.
2. Duration: This rate schedule shall continue in effect until terminated or changed and such termination or change becomes effective in accordance with any applicable regulatory requirements.
3. Services To Be Rendered: Seller may sell, assign, or transfer to a purchaser, pursuant to an agreement negotiated between them, all or a portion of Seller's rights to use of the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility system that Seller has reserved for its own use under a service agreement with the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility or under a service agreement it has acquired from another customer. The purchaser must be an eligible customer under the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility's open access transmission tariff or other tariffs pursuant to which the transmission rights to be transferred to the purchaser were originally obtained from the transmission provider.
4. Sale of Transmission Rights: Seller may sell transmission rights that Seller has reserved for its own use from the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility. Seller may sell, assign, or transfer such transmission rights at the price provided below.
5. Terms and Conditions: Except for price, the terms and conditions under which Seller will sell, assign, or transfer transmission rights on the non-jurisdictional transmitting utility system to a purchaser shall be the terms and conditions governing the original grant of such transmission rights by the transmission provider.
6. Compensation: Seller shall sell, assign, or transfer any transmission rights pursuant to this rate schedule at a price mutually agreed to between Seller and purchaser.
7. Modifications: Seller may unilaterally apply to the Commission or other regulatory agency having jurisdiction for a modification of this rate schedule under Section 205 of the Federal Power Act and the regulations promulgated thereunder. -2-

TransAlta Energy Marketing (U.S.) Inc. FERC RATE SCHEDULE NO. 1
1. Availability: TransAlta Energy Marketing (U.S.) Inc. ("TEMUS") makes electric energy and capacity on a case-by-case basis available under this Rate Schedule to any eligible purchaser for resale at its discretion. TEMUS also makes available to any purchaser ancillary services listed in this Section 1.
(a) PJM: TEMUS offers regulation and frequency response service, energy imbalance service, and operating reserve service (which includes spinning, 10-minute, and 30-minute reserves) for sale into the market administered by PJM Interconnection, L.L.C. ("PJM") and, where the PJM Open Access Transmission Tariff permits, the self-supply of these services to purchasers for a bilateral sale that is used to satisfy the ancillary services requirements of the PJM Office of Interconnection; (b) New York: TEMUS offers regulation and frequency response service, and operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute non-synchronous, 30-minute operating reserves, 10-minute spinning reserves, and 10-minute non-spinning reserves) for sale to purchasers in the market administered by the New York Independent System Operator, Inc.; (c) New England: TEMUS offers regulation and frequency response service (automatic generator control), operating reserve service (which includes 10-minute spinning reserve, 10-minute non-spinning reserve, and 30-minute operating reserve service) to purchasers within the markets administered by the ISO New England, Inc.; (d) California: TEMUS offers regulation service, spinning reserve service, and non-spinning reserve service to the California Independent System Operator Corporation ("CAISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to the CAISO; (e) MISO: TEMUS offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Midcontinent Independent System Operator, Inc. ("MISO") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to MISO. (f) Southwest Power Pool: TEMUS offers regulation service and operating reserve service (which include 10-minute spinning reserve and 10-minute supplemental reserve) for sale to the Southwest Power Pool, Inc. ("SPP") and to others that are self-supplying ancillary services to SPP. (g) Third Party Ancillary Services: TEMUS offers Regulation and Frequency Response Service, Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service, Energy and Generator Imbalance Service, Operating Reserve-Spinning, and Operating Reserve-Supplemental. Sales will not include the following: (1) sales to an RTO or an ISO, i.e., where that entity has no ability to self-supply ancillary services but instead depends on third parties; and (2) sales to a traditional, franchised public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier, or sales where the underlying transmission service is on the system of the public utility affiliated with the third-party supplier. Sales of Operating Reserve-Spinning and Operating Reserve-Supplemental will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except where the Commission has granted authorization. Sales of Regulation and Frequency Response Service and Reactive Supply and Voltage Control Service will not include sales to a public utility that is purchasing ancillary services to satisfy its own open access transmission tariff requirements to offer ancillary services to its own customers, except at rates not to exceed the buying public utility transmission provider's OATT rate for the same service or where the Commission has granted authorization. 2. Applicability: This Rate Schedule is applicable to all sales of energy, capacity and ancillary services by TEMUS to eligible purchasers that are not otherwise subject to a particular rate schedule of TEMUS.
3. Rates: All sales pursuant to this Rate Schedule shall be made at rates negotiated between the purchaser and TEMUS.
4. Other Terms and Conditions: All other terms and conditions for purchases of electric energy and capacity shall be established by agreement between the purchaser and TEMUS.
5. Compliance With Commission Regulations: TEMUS shall comply with the provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, as applicable, and with any conditions the Commission imposes in its orders concerning seller's market-based rate authority, including orders in which the Commission authorizes seller to engage in affiliate sales under this tariff or otherwise restricts or limits the seller's market-based rate authority. Failure to comply with the applicable provisions of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subpart H, and with any orders of the Commission concerning seller's market-based rate authority, will constitute a violation of this tariff.
6. Limitations and Exemptions Regarding Market-Based Rate Authority: TEMUS has no additional limitations on its market-based rate authority. TEMUS has been granted (i) waiver of the accounting and reporting requirements contained in 18 C.F.R. Parts 41, 101, and 141, except sections 141.14 and 141.15; (ii) waiver of 18 C.F.R. Part 35, Subparts B and C, except for sections 35.12(a), 35.13(b), 35.15, and 35.16; and (iii) blanket authorization for the issuance of securities or the assumption of liabilities pursuant to Part 34 of the Commission's regulations. TransAlta Energy Marketing (US), Inc., Docket No. ER98-3184-000, at 1 (June 25, 1998) (unpublished letter order).
7. Seller Category: TEMUS is a Category 2 seller in the Northwest region and a Category 1 seller in all other regions, as defined in 18 C.F.R. 35.36(a).
8. Effective Date: This Rate Schedule shall be effective on the date specified by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission.
